Liverworts are plentiful sources of terpenoids (

; 

; 

) that exhibit vast structural diversity (

) and intriguing biological activities (

; 

; 

; 

). It is reported that many terpenoids that have been isolated from liverworts are enantiomers of those that are found in other higher plants (

, 

; 

). 

Odontoschisma

is one of the rarely chemically investigated genera in liverworts. Up to now, only 

Odontoschisma denudatum

has been chemically described, which is a resource for 
ent
-vibsanes, dolabellanes (

; 

), and two previously undescribed skeletal neodenudatenone-type diterpenoids (

). Moreover, the bioactivities of genus 

Odontoschisma

are rarely studied.


Candida albicans

is one of the normal flora of the healthy human body (

). 

C. albicans

can be a pathogen if the normal host defence mechanisms are impaired (

), and virulence factors are the cause of fungal infection by 

C. albicans
(
Borges et al., 2017
)

. Antifungal resistance that is due to the upregulation of efflux pumps is prevalent in clinical 

Candida

isolates (

; 

). Many terpenoids that have been isolated from liverworts exhibit potent antifungal properties (

). Our previous study identified various liverwort-derived terpenoids (which include eudesmane sesquiterpenoid and labdane lactone), namely, potential efflux pump substrates (PEPSs), that are active against strains that are deficient in efflux pumps but inactive against wild-type strains (

, 

). Some PEPSs produced antifungal activity against wild-type and azole-resistant 

C. albicans

after glucosylation (

), triphenylphosphonium cation conjugation (

) and co-application with efflux pump inhibitors (

). However, they are typically undetected in routine antifungal screening. Thus, the identification of previously undescribed terpenoids from genus 

Odontoschisma

with PEPS properties substantially expands drug discovery channels for antifungal agents.

Odongrossin G ( 7 ) was isolated as a colourless oil. Its molecular formula was determined to be C 20 H 30 O 2 based on its HRESIMS data ( m/ z 320.2581 [M + NH 4 ] + , calcd 320.2584), which correspond to six degrees of unsaturation. The IR spectrum showed an absorption peak at 1711 cm −1 , which was due to the carbonyl group. The 1 H and 13 C NMR data ( Tables 2 and 3 ) revealed four methyls (including two secondary methyls and one vinyl methyl), six methylenes, a three-substituted trans-olefine, a two-substituted trans-olefine [ δ H 5.01 (m) and 5.00 (m); δ C
126.4 and 139.6], a disubstituted vinyl [ δ H 5.05 (br s) and 4.83 (br s); δ C
116.1 and 141.3], and two carbonyl groups ( δ C
215.1 and 204.8). The gross structure of 7 was constructed via a detailed analysis of its 2D NMR data (Figs. S66 and S67). These data of 7 revealed a similar structure to that of denudatenone B (
), except that the location of the double bond was transferred from Δ 7 to Δ 8(17) in 7 , which was further supported by the 1 H– 1 H COSY correlations of H 2 - 17/H 2 -7 and H 2 -17/H 2 -9 and by the HMBC correlations from H 2 -17 to C-6, C-7, C-8 and C-9. A vibsane-type diterpenoid skeleton (
) was suggested. The NOESY correlations of H 3 -15 ( δ H 1.00)/H-2 α , H-2 β /H-13 β , H 3 -15/H-3, H-3/H-7 α , H-3/H-5 α and H-9 β /H-17a indicated the relative configuration of 7 . In addition, the NOESY correlations of H-3/H-5 α and H-11/H-9 β suggested the presence of two E - double bonds at C-3 and C-10, respectively. Accordingly, the relative configuration of 7 was determined. The absolute configuration was supported by ECD calculations, as presented in Fig. S83D. Thus, 7 was identified as 1 S , 3 E , 10 E .

